what kind of color mixing you're using.

9
00:00:34.350 --> 00:00:36.360
So there's different
types of color mixing.

10
00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:38.820
One of them is called
additive color mixing.

11
00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:41.240
And one of them is called
subtractive color mixing.

12
00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:45.900
So when we talk about red, yellow, blue,
well, we're actually really talking about

13
00:00:46.910 --> 00:00:52.430
cyan, magenta, and yellow, plus black.

14
00:00:52.430 --> 00:00:54.920
And that is a subtractive process.

15
00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:58.160
And the reason why it's
a subtractive process is

16
00:00:58.160 --> 00:00:59.910
you're basically subtracting light.

17
00:00:59.910 --> 00:01:02.220
And it's a little bit more
complicated than that,

18
00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:04.870
but that's kind of a base
thing to understand.

19
00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:10.340
When we talk about additive color mixing,
additive color mixing is actually red,

20
00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:14.680
green and blue to make all of the colors.

21
00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:17.655
So here's additive and
subtractive color mixing.

22
00:01:17.655 --> 00:01:22.279
When you're working on the computer,
you're not working with red, yellow and

23
00:01:22.279 --> 00:01:26.564
blue, you're working with red, green and
blue to make all of the colors.

24
00:01:26.564 --> 00:01:30.898
And all of the colors blended
together lead to white,

25
00:01:30.898 --> 00:01:33.702
instead of lead to a darker color.

26
00:01:33.702 --> 00:01:37.592
Sometimes we do things in Photoshop,
or Illustrator, or Sketch,

27
00:01:37.592 --> 00:01:39.093
those kind of documents,

28
00:01:39.093 --> 00:01:43.890
they know that your brains will think
you're using subtractive color processes.

29
00:01:43.890 --> 00:01:45.780
So it will kind of compensate for that,

30
00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:50.080
and make it seem like it
goes in the other direction.

31
00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:51.570
