you get a white flashlight in the middle.

35
00:02:01.870 --> 00:02:05.300
Or if I took red and green flashlights,
and I shown them each other at the wall,

36
00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:07.000
it would turn into a yellow light.

37
00:02:08.810 --> 00:02:12.300
Unlike subtractive color mixing,
and we have C, M, Y.

38
00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:17.040
And really when we mix up C, M, Y,
we get some sort of deep brown,

39
00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:21.390
which is why, in printing processes,
we actually add K, which is black.

40
00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.730
That gives us a richer black than we
could get by mixing all those pigments.

41
00:02:26.730 --> 00:02:30.820
And it's called subtractive color mixing
because basically you have a vehicle.

42
00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:35.230
So if you're painting,
you have a vehicle of oil or

43
00:02:35.230 --> 00:02:37.940
gum Arabic if they're using water color.

