using acrylic paint.

45
00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:42.150
And you have that vehicle.

46
00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:46.910
And then inside that you have all these
kind of particles and pieces of pigments.

47
00:02:46.910 --> 00:02:50.000
And those pigments will
be those pieces of color.

48
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.390
So if I'm using red,
I might use cadmium rock.

49
00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:57.420
Break up the cadmium rock until it
has all of these little pieces.

50
00:02:57.420 --> 00:03:01.050
And then maybe add some alizarin crimson,

51
00:03:01.050 --> 00:03:05.940
some different types of rocks until we're
mixing together and making new colors.

52
00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:09.930
So, we're actually subtracting
light in that instance.

53
00:03:09.930 --> 00:03:12.140
And that's why it's called
subtractive color mixing.

54
00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:15.400
The reason why I'm telling you all of this
is not because you need to remember it

55
00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:16.250
necessarily.

